t, coeffs))\n            }\n\n    # Save learned DAG edges (already done, but let\'s ensure format)\n    # The task says "Save the edges of the DAG to /app/learned_dag.csv"\n    # We already did that.\n\n    # 4. Perform causal intervention on Y, setting its value to 0.0.\n    # In a Linear Gaussian BN, intervention on Y means:\n    # 1. Remove all edges pointing to Y.\n    # 2. Set Y = 0.0 (or Y ~ N(0, 1e-9)).\n    \n    # Let\'s create the intervened parameters.\n    intervened_params = {}\n    for node in cols:\n        if node == \'Y\':\n            # Intervened Y: Y = 0.0\n            intervened_params[node] = {\'intercept\': 0.0, \'coeffs\': {}, \'std\': 1e-9}\n        else:\n            # For other nodes, we need to check if they are descendants of Y.\n            # Actually, in a causal intervention, we only change the node being intervened on\n            # and its descendants. The parents of Y are unaffected.\n            # The nodes that are NOT descendants of Y and are NOT Y itself are unaffected.\n            # Wait, the standard way is:\n            # The distribution of non-descendants of Y is unchanged.\n            # The distribution of Y is fixed to the intervened value.\n            # The distribution of descendants of Y is computed using the new Y.\n            \n            # Let\'s just use the original params for all nodes except Y.\n            # And when we sample, we\'ll use the intervened Y.\n            intervened_params[node] = params[node]\n\n    # Save intervened DAG edges.\n    # The DAG structure itself doesn\'t change (except removing edges to Y).\n    # Wait, "Save the edges of the intervened BN". \n    # If we intervene on Y, we remove edges pointing to Y.\n    intervened_edges = []\n    for f, t in edges:\n        if t != \'Y\':\n            intervened_edges.append((f, t))\n    \n    with open(\'/app/intervened_dag.csv\', \'w\') as f:\n        f.write("to,from\\n")\n        for f_node, t_node in intervened_edges:\n            f.w